  "prompt": "What kind of first jobs do neuroscience majors tend to get?",
  "response": "Neuroscience majors can pursue a variety of first jobs after graduation, depending on their interests and skill sets. Common entry-level positions include:\n\n1. **Research Assistant**: Many graduates work in laboratories, assisting in experimental procedures, data collection, and analysis in academic or private research settings.\n\n2. **Laboratory Technician**: These roles involve hands-on work in a lab, including conducting experiments, maintaining equipment, and managing samples.\n\n3. **Clinical Research Coordinator**: In this role, individuals help manage clinical trials, including recruiting participants, managing data, and ensuring compliance with regulations.\n\n4. **Health Coach or Educator**: Some neuroscience graduates may work in health or wellness settings, providing education on mental health, cognitive health, and wellness strategies.\n\n5. **Pharmaceutical Sales Representative**: Graduates may leverage their scientific background to work in sales for companies that produce drugs related to neurological conditions.\n\n6. **Neuroimaging Technician**: In this role, professionals assist in operating neuroimaging equipment, such as MRI or PET scans in clinical or research settings.\n\n7. **Behavioral Technician**: Graduates may work with individuals with neurological conditions or developmental disorders, providing support and documentation of behavioral intervention.\n\n8. **Science Communication or Education**: Graduates may find roles in educational outreach, teaching, or creating content related to neuroscience for various audiences.\n\n9. **Public Health or Policy Analyst**: Some may enter the public health sector, focusing on neuroscience-related issues, mental health policies, or health education.\n\nThese positions can provide valuable experience and may serve as stepping stones to advanced studies or specialized roles in neuroscience or related fields, such as medicine, psychology, or pharmacology.",
